<TEXT>
as dusk settles on the treelined streets 
of chinas largest city the neon lights flicker cheerfully 
nationwide unrest has quieted but not silenced night life in 
shanghai famed for its songanddance halls allnight restaurants 
and cozy bars 
business slowed down a lot with all the confusion but now 
were back up around 80 percent of normal said a bartender at the 
white egret a 24hour pub and restaurant the problem was that 
with the traffic problems people couldnt get to work and they 
couldnt get here 
students and workers sympathetic to the prodemocracy movement in 
beijing staged their own massive protests after the military crushed 
demonstrations in the capital on june 34 
protesters in shanghai rolled public buses into major 
intersections and let the air out of tires they set up concrete 
roadblocks on other streets 
at their peak the disruptions kept an estimated 50 percent of 
shanghais 12 million residents away from their jobs 
that hurt places like the 5th avenue super bar a tiny spot down 
the street from the posh shanghai hilton 
do you see many customers here asked a hostess at the 5th 
avenue 
there was only one a man sitting in a dark cubicle with another 
hostess in his lap 
the first hostess said the man was a diplomat from one of the 
european consulates these days chinese are nervous and go 
straight home after work and foreigners have gone back to their 
countries she said 
the unrest frightened the foreign community and most expatriates 
left hurriedly after the crackdown in beijing fearing that troops 
would be called into shanghai next 
operators of night spots say foreigners are some of their best 
customers 
the 5th avenue super bar seemed to be trying to make up for lost 
revenue by soaking the few patrons it attracted the bill for a 
beer soda pop and plate of watermelon came to the equivalent of 
32 a months salary for many urban workers 
bartenders and managers say there are about 50 bars in shanghai 
most of which come to life about 6 pm and do not close until the 
wee hours of the morning their small quaint neon signs light up 
the darkness and hostesses with names like jenny and dolly pour 
drinks hold hands and stroke egos 
but even the popular ones arent full 
at the twostory napoleon a few couples sat quietly in 
highbacked chairs in the shadows while a handful of men gathered 
around the counters upstairs and downstairs 
