<TEXT>
the reburial of imre nagy as a martyr 31 
years after his execution as a traitor illustrates the soviet blocs 
increasing tendency to discard official stalinist histories and 
accept events as they were 
encouraged by the soviet exposure of josef stalins excesses 
hungary and poland are confronting longavoided questions about the 
1956 uprising crushed by soviet tanks in the streets of budapest and 
the murder of polish officers by the soviets in the woods of katyn 
rewriting history has been common in the communist world since 
the bolshevik revolution of 1917 
rehabilitation is the term often used when honor is restored 
to former leaders disgraced or executed by ascendant rivals who 
often in their turn also fall from power 
although the current view of history is far more honest there 
still are elements of tailoring it to political ends 
in the soviet union mikhail s gorbachev has expressed 
disapproval of leonid i brezhnev but to some degree has 
rehabilitated nikita s khrushchev whom brezhnev discredited 
brezhnev now stands for the corrupt stagnant policies gorbachev 
seeks to change and khrushchev is seen as the forerunner of the 
reexamination of stalins dictatorship 
nikolai i bukharin and other old bolsheviks purged by stalin 
also have had their respectibility restored 
leon trotsky who commanded the red army in the civil war after 
1917 and lost the power struggle to stalin has not been 
rehabilitated but the kremlins view of him seems kinder trotsky 
was living in mexico in 1940 when an assassin sent by stalin killed 
him with an ax 
in the turbulence of the communist world rehabilitation 
sometimes is quick 
solidarity was born in poland in 1980 during a strike led by 
lech walesa and outlawed in 1982 walesa was detained for months 
and the independent union was reviled 
seven years later solidarity negotiated free elections with the 
government and the voters gave it a stunning victory 
when communist demigods die criticism can grow just as quickly 
president tito was unchallenged in yugoslavia from world war ii 
until his death in 1980 but his policies are being questioned nine 
years later and elaborate birthday festivities have been abandoned 
milovan djilas once heir apparent but later imprisoned by tito 
for nine years because of his dissident views has made a comeback 
after 36 years of being ostracized 
if titos reign had been shorter there would have been many 
fewer doubts cast on his merits djilas a successful writer said 
recently 
fridays reburial in hungary represented almost a complete 
reversal of political fortunes for nagy and janos kadar who took 
over after the soviets crushed the 1956 revolt 
kadar initially reviled gained respect in the 1960s for 
releasing many of those jailed in the revolt and for pursuing 
political and economic reform 
he put brakes on reform in the 1970s however and when he 
resigned last year had become a symbol of economic stagnation and 
political rigidity 
last month the central commmittee of the communist party 
criticized kadar while hailing nagy as a symbol of reform 
this week the government declared said it rejects the 
erroneous and indeed reprehensible political decisions of the past 
the reprisals that followed 1956 
czechoslovakia evidently worried that nagys reburial might draw 
attention to the case of alexander dubcek said thursday enemies 
of socialism might abuse the change in official sentiment 
dubcek was communist party chief in czechoslovakia during the 
prague spring of reform that was crushed by a sovietled 
invasion in august 1968 he now lives in relative obscurity 
</TEXT>
