<TEXT>
after 12 weeks of shelling by syrian 
forces this oncebustling christian enclave north of beirut has 
become a ghost town 
the daily artillery fire which drove most of its 1 million 
residents into underground bunkers and shelters has sapped the life 
from an area once called the monte carlo of the middle east 
although the intensity of shellfire has eased since the arab 
league called for a ceasefire may 11 the christians outnumbered 
and outgunned by syria and its allies have been paralyzed by an 
acute gasoline shortage 
if its not shelling its gas and if its not gas its 
something else said samira khater a secretary 
there is hardly any traffic on the roads few people are able to 
drive to work 
half the shops hidden behind sandbags and earthfilled oildrums 
are shuttered 
factories that survived the ferocious shelling limp along with 
skeleton staffs and whatever fuel they can scrounge 
restaurants are lucky if they get 10 customers a day 
and the night life that once throbbed in the clubs bars and 
restaurants along the mediterranean coastline is dead 
closed is the famous casino du liban overlooking jounieh bay 12 
miles north of beirut where oilrich sheiks from the persian gulf 
and highrollers from around the world once gambled 
it was a regular target for the syrian gunners who have battled 
the forces of christian leader gen michel aoun since march 8 in 
some of the most savage artillery and rocket battles of lebanons 
14year civil war 
about 360 people have been killed and nearly 1400 wounded 
mostly civilians 
the christians are tired and dispirited struggling to cope with 
a grim fatalism 
the ceasefire violated daily by the syrians had raised 
peoples hopes they would be able to pick up the pieces of their 
shattered lives and find some semblance of normality 
instead theres a stillness punctuated only by the periodic 
crump of exploding shells 
the syrians maintain their blockade of the christian enclave 
ringed on its landward sides by hostile moslem forces 
small cargo ships run the gauntlet of shellfire to bring in food 
and ammunition for the besieged christians until a few days ago 
the blockade runners didnt try bringing in gas 
it only takes one hit to blow up a ship loaded with fuel a 
police spokesman said so no one dares take the risk 
one small tanker the 1507ton chemicoral made a run thursday 
with 660000 gallons of gasoline but it was hit by syrian shellfire 
and its cargo burned 
