<TEXT>
color prints by mary stevenson cassatt will get 
their first major show at the national gallery of art beginning 
sunday 100 years after she started making them in france 
cassatts paintings are often exhibited but this will be the 
first comprehensive show to include all 23 of her color etchings 
they were made by drawing lines with a hardened point of metal or 
diamond on copper plates two or three plates to each picture 
she printed the final work from the plates on high quality paper 
often applying several colors of ink to a single plate 
the exhibit also includes prints made from the individual plates 
showing how the pictures developed 
born in 1844 cassatt took her first trip to france at the age of 
seven and settled there 20 years later her father was an investment 
banker once mayor of allegheny city pennsylvania though he at 
first opposed her career he and her mother later lived with her in 
paris and liked being part of the french art world 
the only american among the original french impressionists she 
was introduced to the group by the painter edgar degas she died in 
1926 at her home north of paris the chateau de beaufresne which 
she bought from her earnings as an artist 
cassatts interest in printmaking came from admiration for 
japanese etchers of the previous century especially kitagaro 
utamaro she collected their work and was especially impressed by an 
1890 exhibit in paris 
you must see the japanese come as soon as you can she 
wrote to berthe morisot another of the impressionist painters 
the centerpiece of this show a series of 10 prints on upper 
class womens life in paris derives from the japanese practice of 
producing this type of work in sets but instead of the japanese 
subjects often actors and prostitutes she favored pictures more 
acceptable for americans of the victorian era ladies taking tea 
writing a letter or sitting under a lamp 
a favorite subject of cassatts was a mother with a small child 
she never married or had children of her own 
the exhibit will be at the national gallerys east building until 
aug 27 it will go to the museum of fine arts in boston mass 
sept 9 to nov 5 and to the williams college museum of art 
williamstown mass nov 24 to jan 21 1990 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

