<TEXT>
prizewinning new york times correspondent 
charles mohr who circled the globe and covered washingtons 
corridors of power in a career spanning nearly 40 years died friday 
in a suburban hospital he was 60 
mohr who had a history of heart problems and diabetes had 
suffered a heart attack in his chevy chase md home earlier his 
family said 
as a vietnam war correspondent in the 1960s initially for time 
magazine and later for the times mohr produced stories detailing in 
graphic and moving terms the life of embattled troops in remote 
jungle outposts 
his work was marked by dogged pursuit of facts that went beyond 
what spokesmen provided at official press briefings 
his career also took him to india africa and asia and to the 
presidential campaign trail as well as the white house during the 
terms of presidents dwight d eisenhower lyndon b johnson and 
jimmy carter 
he was among eight reporters and editors who won the 1986 
pulitzer prize for explanatory journalism for the times for a series 
on the star wars spacebased missile system 
mohr a native of loup city neb graduated phi beta kappa from 
the university of nebraska in 1951 he was a reporter for the 
lincoln star in 1950 and 1951 
he spent three years in the chicago bureau of united press before 
joining time in 1954 his assignments for the magazine included san 
francisco the white house new delhi hong kong and saigon 
he joined the times in 1964 and covered the presidential 
campaigns of barry goldwater in 1964 and jimmy carter 1976 reported 
from africa for five years in the 1970s and covered conflicts in the 
mideast including the yom kippur and six day wars 
