in the 1800s the trio of cities at the hudson and mohawk rivers 
troy watervliet and cohoes was ideally situated to become a 
major industrial center in mid19th century america troy mills 
pioneered the bessemer process of converting iron to steel a method 
quickly adopted nationwide 
troy ironmaster henry burden built the worlds biggest hydropower 
waterwheel and his mills churned out a horseshoe every second 
shodding almost all the horses used by the north in the civil war 
in 1826 troy housewife hannah montague tired of washing her 
husbands shirts when only the collars were dirty invented the 
detachable collar that sparked a new industry and earned troy the 
nickname collar city 
about 50 years ago the mills and textile plants began a slow 
fade to the south by the mid1970s the troy area resembled a relic 
of an industrial center with little prosperity 
this area was thriving and bustling with small industries that 
have disappeared from the face of the earth said bill coomley a 
lifelong troy resident 
local officials say theyre disappointed at the decision by 
sterlings owner eastman kodak co to move the pharmaceutical 
research and production plants to the philadelphia area but they 
say many firms could take sterlings place as rensselaer countys 
biggest hightech employer 
sterling plans a gradual withdrawal over two years of its 950 
research jobs and 260 production jobs the research workers will 
have the chance to relocate in pennsylvania the production workers 
wont 
technology companies are so eager to come to rensselaer county 
that if all sterlings people were gone tomorrow i could have 
that land filled up in a month said county executive john buono 
because of such institutions as rensselaer polytechnic institute 
the countrys oldest engineering school troy and its environs have 
attracted pioneers in the major industries of tomorrow officials 
said 
this area has a rich tradition of innovation said michael 
wacholder director of rpis rensselaer technology park which 
houses 35 companies dabbling in the worlds most advanced technology 
the days of the bessemer process and detachable collar are gone 
but the troy area is again at the leading edge of new ideas he said 
what were seeing is just a repeat of what happened in troy in 
the last century he said now were just on to another era 
one firm at the technology park us composites is developing 
strong lightweight composites that may replace steel in auto 
production wacholder said 
about 1000 people work in the 6yearold park selected as one 
of the countrys five top such facilities by the national 
association of university related research parks some of the 
businesses employ as many as 350 people while others have only two 
or three 
but the pioneering research each of those companies is doing now 
could blossom into major industries turning todays twoman shop 
into tomorrows 2000man shop wacholder said 
rensselaer countys jobless rate was 48 percent in april vs 
56 percent statewide and 51 percent nationwide 
like most parts of the country rensselaer county is seeing a 
rise in service sector jobs that generally pay far less than the 
manufacturing jobs that have left the area 
since 1982 the number of manufacturing jobs has been virtually 
unchanged at about 6600 said labor department spokesman james 
ross since 1982 the number of service jobs has grown by 25 percent 
to 12635 in march he said 
those service jobs officials hope will continue to make up for 
the wellpaying bluecollar jobs that inevitably disappear the last 
of troys textile jobs will be gone in july as cluett peabody amp co 
maker of arrow shirts moves its last 385 local jobs to plants in 
georgia 
recruiting employees for businesses at the technology park often 
involves no more than contacting rpi or nearby hudson valley 
community college which stresses technology programs many of the 
businesses including us composites were founded by rpi graduates 
who set up shop in the area to be near its educational resources 
ironically sterling says its moving because rensselaer county 
doesnt have the pool of trained drug researchers and the hightech 
pharmaceutical facilities that philadelphia and nearby southern new 
jersey offer 
new york officials shrug off the apparent slap at the areas 
research resources 
i think they kind of misspeak when they use that buono said 
they want to go to philly to raid existing pharmaceutical 
companies so they can build their staff faster 
unlike the mass pullouts by heavy industry from the northeast 
since the 1960s sterlings exodus is an isolated incident that 
wont be a big obstacle to creating little silicon valley local 
officials say 
whenever i heard people talk about businesses moving from the 
northeast to the sunbelt id say this is the brainbelt 
wacholder said the brains in the northeast developed the 
technology being used in california and the south the brainbelt 
survives 
</TEXT>
