<TEXT>
the revisions in the merger agreement between 
time inc and warner communications inc would leave the new company 
laden with more debt and warner shareholders facing potential tax 
liabilities 
but the companies say even they dont know how much that debt 
burden would be because they have not yet worked out the second 
phase of times proposed twostep buyout of warners stock 
the latest plan was announced friday in an attempt to thwart a 
hostile 175 a share buyout offer from paramount communications inc 
that values time at 107 billion 
in their original merger plan disclosed march 4 time 
shareholders would have received one new share in the new company 
for each time share and warner shareholders would get 0465 shares 
in the new company for every warner share 
the resulting company would have had about 150 million shares 
but time president nj nicholas jr said the marketplace 
indicated through times stock price it was unhappy with the 
terms of that agreement 
it was telling us you didnt do the right deal he said in 
an interview 
in the past 10 days the time and warner boards negotiated a 
revision in the merger agreement that call for time to make a tender 
offer for warner 
under that plan time will offer 70 a share for 100 million of 
warners approximately 200 million shares 
that portion of the deal would cost 7 billion and warner 
shareholders who may have acquired their stock for less than 70 a 
share would face a potential capital gains tax liability upon 
tendering their shares 
in the second phase of the deal each remaining warner share will 
be converted for an asyet unspecified combination of cash stock or 
debt 
both phases of the warner buyout would cost a total of about 14 
billion warner would also bring 1 billion in debt to the new 
company boosting the total value of the merger to about 15 billion 
the companies said a bank group led by manufacturers hanover 
corp and bankers trust co already have committed to provide 15 
billion for the deal and have said they can arrange up 14 billion 
in additional financing 
time and warner also said their combined cash flow after a merger 
would be adequate to service their debt load 
if the second phase of the deal excludes issuance of new stock 
time would be left with about 57 million shares the same as it has 
now 
but warner and time officials hope that the market will value the 
time shares more highly because the new company will have a 
substantially broader asset base 
